APPENDIX B: PROBABILITY-WEIGHTED RISK ASSESSMENT
================================================================================

This appendix provides quantitative risk assessment for major strategic 
assumptions. Probabilities are based on expert consultation, historical 
precedent analysis, and current trajectory modeling.

RISK SCENARIO | PROBABILITY | IMPACT | MITIGATION STATUS
              | (2026-2030) | SEVERITY |
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Alliance      | 25-35%      | HIGH     | Positive incentives, graduated
fragmentation |             |          | commitments, annual reviews

Chinese       | 20-30%      | MEDIUM   | Parallel R&D tracks, acceleration
materials     |             |          | clauses, intelligence monitoring
breakthrough  |             |          |

Taiwan        | 15-25%      | CRITICAL | Multi-layer deterrence, fab
conflict      |             |          | redundancy, military aid

Synthetic     | 40-50%      | MEDIUM   | Realistic timelines (3-5 years),
materials     |             |          | phased milestones, alternatives
delays        |             |          |

WTO challenges| 30-40%      | LOW      | Technocratic framing, security
to Pax Silica |             |          | exceptions, multilateral legitimacy

Domestic      | 20-30%      | HIGH     | Bipartisan CHIPS Act support, job
political     |             |          | creation in swing states, national
reversal      |             |          | security framing

Global South  | 35-45%      | MEDIUM   | 10% R&D allocation for tech
backlash      |             |          | transfer, inclusive rhetoric,
              |             |          | development partnerships

METHODOLOGY: Probabilities derived from historical base rates of similar 
geopolitical initiatives, expert elicitation (15 specialists in international 
relations, technology policy, and materials science), and extrapolation from 
current trends. Impact severity assessed based on potential disruption to 
strategic objectives.


================================================================================
APPENDIX C: BASELINE PERFORMANCE METRICS
================================================================================

The 70-80% value capture target requires baseline context. This appendix 
provides current state comparisons and trajectory analysis.

CURRENT STATE (2025):
• U.S. semiconductor market share: ~47% of global revenue, concentrated in 
  design and high-end manufacturing
• China semiconductor market share: ~24% of global revenue, concentrated in 
  mature nodes and assembly
• Taiwan (TSMC) market share: ~54% of global foundry revenue, ~90% of 
  leading-edge nodes
• U.S. rare earth dependency: ~80% of rare earth imports from China or 
  China-processed materials

TARGET STATE (2030):
• U.S. + Pax Silica allies semiconductor value capture: 70-80% of high-margin 
  segments (design, EUV lithography, leading-edge foundry, AI accelerators)
• China semiconductor access: Limited to 14nm+ nodes for most applications, with 
  exceptions for consumer electronics
• Taiwan concentration risk: Reduced from 90% to 65% of leading-edge production 
  through geographic diversification
• U.S. rare earth dependency: Reduced from 80% to 40% through synthetic 
  substitutes (30%) and diversified sourcing (30%)

TRAJECTORY ANALYSIS:

The 70-80% target represents VALUE CAPTURE not volume. Current U.S. position 
already captures ~60% of semiconductor industry profits despite lower unit 
volume, due to concentration in high-margin design (Qualcomm, NVIDIA, AMD) and 
equipment (Applied Materials, Lam Research). The Pax Silica framework aims to:

1. Maintain design dominance through AI chip leadership and continued R&D 
   investment
2. Expand manufacturing capacity in allied nations, reducing Taiwan 
   concentration while maintaining technological edge
3. Preserve equipment monopolies (ASML EUV) through export controls and 
   collaborative development
4. Eliminate rare earth vulnerability as potential counter-leverage

Historical precedent supports feasibility: U.S. maintained 70%+ value capture in 
commercial aviation (Boeing, engine manufacturers, avionics) for decades despite 
global competition. The semiconductor industry's higher barriers to entry 
(capital intensity, technical complexity) suggest similar sustainability if 
properly managed.

